illion  total equity us billion  number of employees  apr  website wwwarmstrongcom armstrong world industries inc is a pennsylvania corporation incorporated in  it is an international designer and manufacturer of floors and ceilings based in lancaster pennsylvania armstrong operates  plants in eight countries and has approximately  employees worldwide in  armstrong’s net sales were  billion with operating income of  million armstrong world industries inc emerged from chapter  reorganization on october   its stock began trading on the new york stock exchange october   under the ticker symbol awi the armstrong world industries inc asbestos personal injury settlement trust holds approximately  of awi’s outstanding common shares armstrongs “fourth amended plan of reorganization as modified” dated february   and confirmed by us district court judge eduardo robreno in august  become effective oct   the plan includes a comprehensive settlement resolving awi’s asbestos liability by establishing and funding a trust to compensate all current and future asbestos personal injury claimants the company had filed for reorganization december   with the federal bankruptcy court in delaware for reorganization under chapter  because pending asbestos injury claims appeared to exceed the value of the company and were growing “in addition to resolving awi’s asbestos liability we used the time in chapter  to restructure our flooring business to make it more competitive” mr lockhart said “we made substantial improvements in our cost structure by closing several plants and streamlining our workforce in the us we have also expanded capacity to manufacture wood flooring broadened our product lines and improved product quality and customer service” on march   armstrong world industries inc and npm capital nv entered into an agreement to sell tapijtfabriek h desseaux nv and its subsidiaries the principal operating companies in armstrong’s european textile and sports flooring business segment to npm capital nv the sale was finalized in april  on february   armstrong world industries inc announced that it was initiating a review of its strategic alternatives contents  history  armstrong manor  divisions  environmental record  manufacturing locations  references  external links historyedit former armstrong cork company building in pittsburgh pennsylvania built circa  in  thomas m armstrong the son of scottishirish immigrants from derry joined with john d glass to open a oneroom shop in pittsburgh pennsylvania carving bottle stoppers from cork by hand their first deliveries were made in a wheelbarrow armstrong was a business pioneer in some respects he branded each cork he shipped as early as  and soon was putting a written guarantee in each burlap bag of corks he shipped from his big new factory the company grew to be the largest cork supplier in the world by the s the company incorporated in  cork began being displaced by other closures but the company introduced insulating corkboard and brick in  two years before he died thomas armstrong concluded that the solid foundation of the future was covered with linoleum and construction began on a new factory in a cornfield at the edge of lancaster pennsylvania in  armstrong linoleum was first offered to the trade after corkboard the logical move was to fiberboard and then to ceiling board cork tile and linoleum led to vinyl flooring then ceramic tile laminate flooring and carpeting in  armstrong cork signed with the batton company advertising agency a relationship that continues to this day through their corporate descendants in  armstrong acquired triangle pacific corp a leading manufacturer of hardwood flooring and kitchenbathroom cabinets in  armstrong’s annual net sales total usbillion armstrong cabinets is no longer owned by armstrong world industries the business was sold to american industrial partners on october   in  armstrong spun off the flooring business into a new company armstrong flooring nyse afi armstrong manoredit formerly known as armstrong manor the property is currently owned by rodgers  associates of lancaster pennsylvania and is now called the manor the armstrong manor was originally purchased by armstrong world industries for use as a central location to house the company’s young sales trainees the home was later used in other capacities such as meeting space and temporary housing for visiting employees armstrong owned the property from may  to december  the property is located in lancaster pennsylvania the oldest part of armstrong manor originally known as bloomington farm was built in  by david p locher a prosperous local tanner banker and farmer the acre property remained a part of locher’s estate until april   when grove locher purchased the property for  on may   the then pittsburgh pennsylvaniabased armstrong cork company purchased the mansion from grove locher and his wife for  the company’s second president charles d armstrong was disturbed by the conditions in which his son dwight and other new sales employees were living within various rented housing across lancaster cd armstrong and his wife gertrude virginia ludden armstrong were also aware of the difficulties with the transition from campus life to industrial living and desired a more comfortable living space for their sales trainees mr and mrs armstrong also wanted to have a suitable location for business meetings with visiting employees from other areas the house was used as a living space for the sales trainees all single men during their month training program at the lancaster pa flooring plant the company spent an additional  on renovations and renamed the property armstrong manor more recently the manor provided housing for visiting armstrong employees and customers and continued to fulfill its role as a meeting space the property also had a facilities maintenance department plumbers electricians and a mailroom to support the property in november  armstrong world industries announced its plan to close armstrong manor by the end of the year citing that the manor and the facilities department were no longer part of the “…core to being a building products manufacturer” armstrong manor was sold to rodgers  associates a wealth management firm based in lancaster pennsylvania on december   divisionsedit in the s the armstrong cork products company and sherwin williams company were the largest industrial customers for hemp fiber in  armstrong bought whitall tatum a leading manufacturer of glass standoff insulators for utility poles since  the existing molds were eventually replaced with molds bearing the armstrong name in april  the business was sold to kerr glass manufacturing corporation demand was rapidly dropping as utilities were converting to ceramics or going underground and kerr moved production to their dunkirk indiana factory in the mids and ceasing production several years after that during world war ii armstrong made caliber round ammunition wing tips for airplanes cork sound insulation for submarines and camouflage in  a group of leading industrialists that included alfred p sloan of general motors frank w abrams of standard oil company of new jersey henry ford ii of ford motor company john l mccaffrey of international harvester irving s olds of united states steel corporation henning w prentis of armstrong cork company and laird bell of weyerhauser timber formed the council for financial aid to education which increased corporate gifts to colleges from  million annually to  million annually over ten years in  armstrong cork company created armstrong contracting and supply corporation armstrong cork had done insulation contracting since the early th century originally focusing on cork products gradually there was greater emphasis on high temperature insulation in  this business was sold in a leveraged buyout to  existing and retired employees of the contracting company which became irex corporation cue inc started as the polyurethane division of armstrong cork in the s cue comes from custom urethane elastomers the fluorocarbon company of anaheim california bought the division in  on april   a group of seven employees acquired the division in a leveraged buyout in  armstrong bought phoenix chair company following up with founders furniture company in  western carolina furniture company in  and both thomasville furniture and caldwell furniture in  in the s they expanded with a lowend bedroom furniture line they bought gilliam furniture in  bought and repurposed the former stehle polyester factory in carysbrook virginia later that year bought westchester group in  and gordons in  as well as making a major expansion to thomasville that yearcitation needed in  thomasville furniture was sold to interco which became furniture brands international a leading furniture manufacturer with such brands as broyhill and lane environmental recordedit armstrong holdings inc used to produce asbestos either of two incombustible chemicalresistant fibrous mineral forms of impure magnesium silicate used for fireproofing electrical insulation building materials brake linings and chemical filters which was required by law before they started to manufacture interior furnishings on november   it was reported that armstrong holdings inc was facing about  asbestos personal injury claims that would cost between  million and  billion through  they filed bankruptcy because of all their asbestos liabilities armstrong no longer produces asbestos and now makes vinyl and wood flooring and other interior furnishings armstrong now claims we offer you a proud heritage of innovation commitment to environmental sustainability and operations based on integrity respect diversity continuous improvement and a passion for safety manufacturing locationsedit acproducts inc is the seventh largest manufacturer and distributor of cabinets in the united states the company offers six wood species for its stock and semicustom cabinets including cherry maple oak birch plantation hardwood and laminatethermofoil and serves over  customers through a network of  facilities consisting of acpbranded showroomselection centers regional distribution centers and warehouses all in the united states acp is headquartered in the colony tx with manufacturing operations in thompsontown pa cabinet production facilities were owned by armstrong world industries but are now under american industrial partners with products being sold under the acpi branding  the company manufactures flooring products in the us in beech creek pennsylvania beverly west virginia center texas jackson mississippi jackson tennessee kankakee illinois lancaster pennsylvania oneida tennessee somerset kentucky south gate california statesville north carolina stillwater oklahoma warren arkansas west plains missouri titusville pennsylvania and internationally in shanghai china braeside victoria thomastown victoria teesside england and holmsund sweden they produce ceiling products in the us in beaver falls pennsylvania hilliard ohio macon georgia marietta pennsylvania mobile alabama pensacola florida st helens oregon and internationally in rankweil austria shanghai china stafford england thornaby england team valley england pontarlier france münster germany st gallen switzerland and zurich switzerland in yelabuga russia there are wave plants in benton harbor michigan henderson nevada aberdeen maryland shanghai china prouvy france team valley england and madrid spain wave is a joint venture with worthington industries there are ade facilities in dendermonde belgium waasmunster belgium bietigheimbissingen germany delmenhorst germany and waalwijk netherlands referencesedit  a b c d e f armstrong world industries form k annual report filing date feb   pdf secdatabasecom retrieved jan     armstrong world industries form q quarterly report filing date oct   secdatabasecom retrieved jan     armstrong world industries form k current report filing date nov   pdf secdataba